<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n14212e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14212e">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14212e"> 212(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> reiving ship</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">One of the simplest forms of crooning or keening, the very short refrain here cuts remorselessly into each verse-line. From Widow Macdonald also we learnt the electrifying &ldquo;<mark>Reiving Ship</mark>&rdquo; (p. 45). Strange that the old women should have sung to us these virile pirate chants! The &ldquo;A ho hi! Hirm bo!&rdquo; of its refrain is a rapturously reiving cry, and the ship in her course in Kenneth Macleod&apos;s English: <br>&ldquo;Grinds beneath her gray-blue limpets, <br>Crunches curving whelks to sand-drift.&rdquo; <small> Marjory Kennedy-Fraser and Kenneth Macleod, <a name="MKSH" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MKSH"><cite title="source">Songs of the Hebrides</cite></a> (1917) p. xvi</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
